00:37:40.625 --> 00:37:44.696 align:middle line:84%
Doctor Taylor said, "I don't
see this as decades away.

00:37:44.696 --> 00:37:48.499 align:middle line:84%
Right now medical science
is waiting for an human art

00:37:48.499 --> 00:37:52.136 align:middle line:84%
to be put in a human
being from a cadabra."

00:37:52.136 --> 00:37:54.405 align:middle line:84%
I remember her telling
me that she's concerned

00:37:54.405 --> 00:38:00.078 align:middle line:84%
that 3,000 people a year die
waiting for a heart transplant.

00:38:00.078 --> 00:38:01.746 align:middle line:90%
And this could be the answer."

00:38:01.746 --> 00:38:06.584 align:middle line:84%
So, at Lake Forest university
and at university of Pittsburgh

00:38:06.584 --> 00:38:09.687 align:middle line:84%
and several other
University in the field

00:38:09.687 --> 00:38:11.889 align:middle line:90%
to regenerate the [inaudible].

00:38:11.889 --> 00:38:18.162 align:middle line:84%
They are building
livers, kidneys, bladders

00:38:18.162 --> 00:38:22.867 align:middle line:84%
and other organ parts that can
be implanted into a human being.

00:38:22.867 --> 00:38:28.439 align:middle line:84%
Now a lot of the veterans are
getting replacement ears, limbs

00:38:28.439 --> 00:38:29.374 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Noses.

00:38:29.374 --> 00:38:30.775 align:middle line:90%
>> Christian Wilde: Noses.

00:38:30.775 --> 00:38:34.412 align:middle line:84%
Yes. They can build a they can
make a matrix out of the ear.

00:38:34.412 --> 00:38:36.547 align:middle line:90%
It'll be exactly like your ear.

00:38:36.547 --> 00:38:41.486 align:middle line:84%
They can use an extra
cellular material.

00:38:41.486 --> 00:38:45.223 align:middle line:84%
And in eight weeks, that's a
new ear they could implant.

00:38:45.223 --> 00:38:46.224 align:middle line:90%
Ready to go.

00:38:46.224 --> 00:38:47.492 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
That's truly amazing.

00:38:47.492 --> 00:38:49.227 align:middle line:84%
Let's take some questions
for Christian Wilde here.

00:38:49.227 --> 00:38:50.728 align:middle line:90%
Just raise your hands.

00:38:50.728 --> 00:38:53.297 align:middle line:90%
Anybody? Yes, sir.

00:38:53.297 --> 00:38:56.401 align:middle line:84%
>> What sort of ethical
and legal issues do you run

00:38:56.401 --> 00:39:03.474 align:middle line:84%
into with these kinds of
trials and surgical procedures?

00:39:03.474 --> 00:39:04.342 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde:
That's a good question.

00:39:04.342 --> 00:39:05.676 align:middle line:90%
These are monitored by the FDA.

00:39:05.676 --> 00:39:09.914 align:middle line:84%
They cannot do this
without FDA approval.

00:39:09.914 --> 00:39:13.918 align:middle line:84%
And they are watched
very scrupulously.

00:39:13.918 --> 00:39:18.523 align:middle line:84%
They have to absolutely report
on everything it goes on.

00:39:18.523 --> 00:39:20.758 align:middle line:84%
I have not heard
of anybody dying

00:39:20.758 --> 00:39:23.294 align:middle line:84%
from this heart procedure
that I mentioned.

00:39:23.294 --> 00:39:26.898 align:middle line:84%
And now they're using
donor stem cells

00:39:26.898 --> 00:39:31.669 align:middle line:84%
from other people instead
of the thigh muscle.

00:39:31.669 --> 00:39:33.037 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Why is that?

00:39:33.037 --> 00:39:35.339 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde: It's just
see they are more prevalent.

00:39:35.339 --> 00:39:37.942 align:middle line:90%
They can get those from anybody.

00:39:37.942 --> 00:39:40.411 align:middle line:84%
And eventually what'll
happen George is it's going

00:39:40.411 --> 00:39:42.213 align:middle line:90%
to be off the shelf.

00:39:42.213 --> 00:39:47.685 align:middle line:84%
The doctor will be able to
order stem cells off the shelf

00:39:47.685 --> 00:39:50.188 align:middle line:90%
and use them for your body.

00:39:50.188 --> 00:39:53.524 align:middle line:90%
And another answer for that.

00:39:53.524 --> 00:39:56.861 align:middle line:84%
If the pharmaceutical
companies were going to spend 50

00:39:56.861 --> 00:40:00.565 align:middle line:84%
to a hundred million dollars
on a trial, they are not going

00:40:00.565 --> 00:40:04.001 align:middle line:84%
to make any money
doing this procedure.

00:40:04.001 --> 00:40:08.072 align:middle line:84%
It takes I've been in this
procedure, it takes 45 minutes.

00:40:08.072 --> 00:40:10.508 align:middle line:90%
And I'm talking to the patient.

00:40:10.508 --> 00:40:12.510 align:middle line:90%
And he's listening to music.

00:40:12.510 --> 00:40:14.612 align:middle line:90%
My CD. [Chuckles]

00:40:14.612 --> 00:40:17.215 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Which we're
going to have you sing.

00:40:17.215 --> 00:40:21.919 align:middle line:84%
Let's take another question
from our Beyond Belief cam.

00:40:21.919 --> 00:40:23.421 align:middle line:90%
>> Hi Chris.

00:40:23.421 --> 00:40:25.523 align:middle line:90%
I'm Melissa from California.

00:40:25.523 --> 00:40:27.558 align:middle line:84%
I was wondering what
your thoughts were

00:40:27.558 --> 00:40:31.596 align:middle line:84%
on freezing the umbilical
cord for stem cells.

00:40:31.596 --> 00:40:32.897 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde:
Oh, good question.

00:40:32.897 --> 00:40:33.865 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: That seems

00:40:33.865 --> 00:40:35.833 align:middle line:84%
to be going away
somewhat, isn't it?

00:40:35.833 --> 00:40:37.969 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde: I
want to try to change it.

00:40:37.969 --> 00:40:39.604 align:middle line:84%
How many of you have
heard about that?

00:40:39.604 --> 00:40:41.706 align:middle line:90%
Storing the umbilical cord.

00:40:41.706 --> 00:40:43.107 align:middle line:84%
I'll give you the
rational for it.

00:40:43.107 --> 00:40:44.175 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
It's controversial.

00:40:44.175 --> 00:40:45.877 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde:
Controversial.

00:40:45.877 --> 00:40:48.112 align:middle line:90%
But here's the good point.

00:40:48.112 --> 00:40:52.717 align:middle line:84%
You don't know whether your
child is going to be able

00:40:52.717 --> 00:40:55.152 align:middle line:90%
to walk for a couple of years.

00:40:55.152 --> 00:40:58.489 align:middle line:84%
You don't know if your child
is going to be able to talk.

00:40:58.489 --> 00:41:00.825 align:middle line:90%
You're watching all the time.

00:41:00.825 --> 00:41:08.099 align:middle line:84%
It's possible your child has a
defect from birth in general.

00:41:08.099 --> 00:41:10.601 align:middle line:90%
Childhood diseases show up.

00:41:10.601 --> 00:41:15.306 align:middle line:84%
Up to 18, there's many diseases
that can strike a child.

00:41:15.306 --> 00:41:19.877 align:middle line:84%
But if science, by then,
has a cure for this disease

00:41:19.877 --> 00:41:25.616 align:middle line:84%
with stem cells and you have
stored the blood, the cord blood

00:41:25.616 --> 00:41:28.085 align:middle line:84%
from the birth, they
can take that

00:41:28.085 --> 00:41:30.621 align:middle line:84%
and purify it and
heal that child.

00:41:30.621 --> 00:41:32.456 align:middle line:90%
I want to give you an example.

00:41:32.456 --> 00:41:37.929 align:middle line:84%
At Duke University, director of
pediatrics, Joanne Kurtzberg,

00:41:37.929 --> 00:41:41.732 align:middle line:84%
has brought a child
who has cerebral palsy.

00:41:41.732 --> 00:41:44.235 align:middle line:84%
The reason they are
bring the child to her is

00:41:44.235 --> 00:41:49.707 align:middle line:84%
because she's an advocate of
umbilical storage of stem cells.

00:41:49.707 --> 00:41:53.711 align:middle line:84%
She says, "Because you have
done that, I can take blood

00:41:53.711 --> 00:41:56.047 align:middle line:90%
from there and I can purify it.

00:41:56.047 --> 00:41:59.116 align:middle line:84%
Take out the abhorrent
gene that's in it.

00:41:59.116 --> 00:42:01.886 align:middle line:84%
And inject it into the
child through his hand.

00:42:01.886 --> 00:42:05.556 align:middle line:84%
And six months later, that
child is completely free

00:42:05.556 --> 00:42:07.058 align:middle line:90%
of cerebral palsy.

00:42:07.058 --> 00:42:10.595 align:middle line:84%
And on my website, under
stem cell miracles,

00:42:10.595 --> 00:42:11.996 align:middle line:90%
you can see a story.

00:42:11.996 --> 00:42:14.966 align:middle line:84%
It'll bring tears to your eyes,
of a little two year old girl

00:42:14.966 --> 00:42:19.503 align:middle line:84%
who had been photographed in
her problems as she developed

00:42:19.503 --> 00:42:25.176 align:middle line:84%
and found out she had mobility
problems and speech problems.

00:42:25.176 --> 00:42:29.680 align:middle line:84%
And because of stem cells,
she's a hundred percent.

00:42:29.680 --> 00:42:30.715 align:middle line:90%
And you'll see it.

00:42:30.715 --> 00:42:34.185 align:middle line:84%
It was a TV thing
that I put on there.

00:42:34.185 --> 00:42:35.786 align:middle line:84%
And now they find
that they may be able

00:42:35.786 --> 00:42:38.689 align:middle line:90%
to help other family members.

00:42:38.689 --> 00:42:40.491 align:middle line:90%
So, it's an investment.

00:42:40.491 --> 00:42:42.660 align:middle line:84%
Like George said,
it is an investment.

00:42:42.660 --> 00:42:46.030 align:middle line:84%
Grandparents will sometimes
do it for their newborn.

00:42:46.030 --> 00:42:47.164 align:middle line:90%
Say, "Let me just do it.

00:42:47.164 --> 00:42:48.833 align:middle line:84%
If I can only afford to
do it for three years,

00:42:48.833 --> 00:42:49.867 align:middle line:90%
I'll do it for three years.

00:42:49.867 --> 00:42:52.737 align:middle line:84%
It might cost $75
a month, I figure."

00:42:52.737 --> 00:42:56.040 align:middle line:84%
And at that point you find
out if the child can talk.

00:42:56.040 --> 00:42:57.975 align:middle line:90%
If the child can walk.

00:42:57.975 --> 00:43:00.077 align:middle line:84%
You know? And think
what a blessing it is

00:43:00.077 --> 00:43:03.714 align:middle line:84%
that you can save
that child's misery.

00:43:03.714 --> 00:43:05.616 align:middle line:90%
Cerebral palsy among them.

00:43:05.616 --> 00:43:07.718 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Let's take
another question in the audience

00:43:07.718 --> 00:43:09.720 align:middle line:90%
for Christian Wilde yes, sir?

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:10.888 align:middle line:90%
>> Hi Christian.

00:43:10.888 --> 00:43:13.758 align:middle line:84%
Is plaque buildup
in the arteries one

00:43:13.758 --> 00:43:16.093 align:middle line:84%
of the main causes
of heart attacks?

00:43:16.093 --> 00:43:19.463 align:middle line:84%
And is there any way
to reduce or eliminate

00:43:19.463 --> 00:43:22.566 align:middle line:90%
that by diet and exercise alone?

00:43:22.566 --> 00:43:25.903 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde: Unless
you have a predisposition

00:43:25.903 --> 00:43:29.740 align:middle line:84%
in your family line, in the
hidden causes, what we talk

00:43:29.740 --> 00:43:35.413 align:middle line:84%
about a lot is what could
have taken your grandfather

00:43:35.413 --> 00:43:41.952 align:middle line:84%
out at 54 years of age and then
his son at 50 years of age.

00:43:41.952 --> 00:43:45.356 align:middle line:84%
And now you're 50 years
of age, and you wonder,

00:43:45.356 --> 00:43:47.725 align:middle line:84%
what's going on in
my family line?

00:43:47.725 --> 00:43:51.228 align:middle line:84%
If they can detector what's
going on now, which we talk

00:43:51.228 --> 00:43:53.898 align:middle line:84%
about in the book,
most physicians don't.

00:43:53.898 --> 00:43:56.300 align:middle line:84%
They just treat you
as an individual.

00:43:56.300 --> 00:43:59.236 align:middle line:84%
But those hidden factors have
been passed on from generations

00:43:59.236 --> 00:44:01.772 align:middle line:90%
to generations to generations.

00:44:01.772 --> 00:44:05.109 align:middle line:84%
And you will pass them onto
your children, unfortunately.

00:44:05.109 --> 00:44:09.180 align:middle line:84%
Unless you learn to go
in and detect what it is

00:44:09.180 --> 00:44:10.614 align:middle line:90%
that you've inherited.

00:44:10.614 --> 00:44:15.386 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you just have
a normal lifestyle.

00:44:15.386 --> 00:44:16.454 align:middle line:90%
And you have built

00:44:16.454 --> 00:44:21.258 align:middle line:84%
up calcification
plaque, in your arteries.

00:44:21.258 --> 00:44:25.329 align:middle line:84%
Doctor Doris Taylor also
addresses that issue.

00:44:25.329 --> 00:44:28.666 align:middle line:84%
She took a young mouse
and she took an old mouse.

00:44:28.666 --> 00:44:33.504 align:middle line:84%
She induced a great
amount of plaque

00:44:33.504 --> 00:44:36.640 align:middle line:84%
in the artery of
the older mouse.

00:44:36.640 --> 00:44:41.145 align:middle line:84%
And then she took stem
cells from a young mouse

00:44:41.145 --> 00:44:45.816 align:middle line:84%
and injected them into that
mouse, the older mouse.

00:44:45.816 --> 00:44:49.186 align:middle line:84%
And she could see
before and after.

00:44:49.186 --> 00:44:53.858 align:middle line:84%
The stem cells eroded
and took out 95 percent

00:44:53.858 --> 00:44:56.260 align:middle line:90%
of the plaque buildup.

00:44:56.260 --> 00:44:58.229 align:middle line:90%
But the stress is a factor.

00:44:58.229 --> 00:44:59.263 align:middle line:90%
[Inaudible] is a factor.

00:44:59.263 --> 00:45:01.398 align:middle line:90%
Homocysteine's a factor.

00:45:01.398 --> 00:45:04.268 align:middle line:90%
Definitely CRP is a factor.

00:45:04.268 --> 00:45:06.203 align:middle line:90%
All of these things contribute.

00:45:06.203 --> 00:45:08.439 align:middle line:90%
Smoking is still number one.

00:45:08.439 --> 00:45:12.610 align:middle line:84%
We've got Beyond Belief cam
question for you Christian.

00:45:12.610 --> 00:45:14.211 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look.

00:45:14.211 --> 00:45:17.114 align:middle line:84%
>> Hi Christian, my name
is mark from a Washington,

00:45:17.114 --> 00:45:20.417 align:middle line:84%
D.C. the scientist tell us
that one day they'll be able

00:45:20.417 --> 00:45:22.653 align:middle line:90%
to replace our body parts.

00:45:22.653 --> 00:45:25.589 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: So, let's
replace these body parts.

00:45:25.589 --> 00:45:26.590 align:middle line:90%
>> Christian Wilde: Yes.

00:45:26.590 --> 00:45:31.896 align:middle line:84%
You know, a person
dies prematurely.

00:45:31.896 --> 00:45:35.399 align:middle line:84%
To answer George's question
about the fact that people die

00:45:35.399 --> 00:45:39.003 align:middle line:84%
and live 40 years, 35,
40 years then they die.

00:45:39.003 --> 00:45:44.241 align:middle line:84%
A person dies because of
liver failure, kidney failure,

00:45:44.241 --> 00:45:46.944 align:middle line:90%
heart failure, lung failure.

00:45:46.944 --> 00:45:48.479 align:middle line:90%
And have they not had any

00:45:48.479 --> 00:45:51.382 align:middle line:84%
of those diseases they
probably would have lived a 30

00:45:51.382 --> 00:45:53.717 align:middle line:90%
or 40 years longer.

00:45:53.717 --> 00:45:58.956 align:middle line:84%
Now, because of doctor Doris
Taylor's work, they can replace

00:45:58.956 --> 00:46:01.892 align:middle line:90%
and will replace that kidney.

00:46:01.892 --> 00:46:03.093 align:middle line:90%
And you're good to go.

00:46:03.093 --> 00:46:05.596 align:middle line:84%
It's like the car we
were talking about.

00:46:05.596 --> 00:46:07.565 align:middle line:84%
You need to put the
transmission in it.

00:46:07.565 --> 00:46:08.899 align:middle line:90%
So this car is good.

00:46:08.899 --> 00:46:11.135 align:middle line:84%
Now if I put a new
transmission in it,

00:46:11.135 --> 00:46:14.471 align:middle line:84%
this person's body
is back to normal

00:46:14.471 --> 00:46:16.941 align:middle line:90%
if I can replace that liver.

00:46:16.941 --> 00:46:20.244 align:middle line:84%
If I can replace that
lung or those lungs.

00:46:20.244 --> 00:46:22.680 align:middle line:84%
And that's all being
done right now.

00:46:22.680 --> 00:46:25.683 align:middle line:84%
And then once it
gets FDA approved,

00:46:25.683 --> 00:46:27.017 align:middle line:90%
you will know about it.

00:46:27.017 --> 00:46:30.688 align:middle line:84%
But I can tell you right
now, it is being done.

00:46:30.688 --> 00:46:33.057 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: So, if you
were to go up to someone

00:46:33.057 --> 00:46:36.660 align:middle line:84%
who would come up to you
and say, "What do I do?"

00:46:36.660 --> 00:46:38.829 align:middle line:84%
Why don't you spell out,
first of all, and we'll get

00:46:38.829 --> 00:46:41.932 align:middle line:84%
into the stem cell treatments
and some things people can do,

00:46:41.932 --> 00:46:45.269 align:middle line:84%
but in terms of just
taking care of your heart,

00:46:45.269 --> 00:46:48.539 align:middle line:84%
what do you recommend
people do right now?

00:46:48.539 --> 00:46:49.940 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde:
Coenzyme Q10.

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:51.742 align:middle line:84%
If you're taking this
[inaudible] drug,

00:46:51.742 --> 00:46:54.311 align:middle line:84%
how many of you are
taking [inaudible] drugs?

00:46:54.311 --> 00:46:55.412 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Cholesterol lowers.

00:46:55.412 --> 00:46:56.413 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde:
Only one person?

00:46:56.413 --> 00:46:57.548 align:middle line:90%
This is a healthy group.

00:46:57.548 --> 00:47:01.151 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: This
is a healthy group.

00:47:01.151 --> 00:47:02.586 align:middle line:90%
>> Christian Wilde: Yes.

00:47:02.586 --> 00:47:07.091 align:middle line:84%
If you take any [inaudible]
drug you're depleting your heart

00:47:07.091 --> 00:47:09.994 align:middle line:90%
of Coenzyme Q10.

00:47:09.994 --> 00:47:14.798 align:middle line:84%
Coenzyme Q10 is required of
every muscle of your body.

00:47:14.798 --> 00:47:19.770 align:middle line:84%
If you got a prescription
in Canada for any

00:47:19.770 --> 00:47:20.971 align:middle line:90%
of the [inaudible] drugs,

00:47:20.971 --> 00:47:25.209 align:middle line:84%
you would also be told you
must take Coenzyme Q10.

00:47:25.209 --> 00:47:26.777 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Why
don't they tell you here?

00:47:26.777 --> 00:47:29.513 align:middle line:84%
>> Christian Wilde: That's
an interesting question.

00:47:29.513 --> 00:47:31.649 align:middle line:84%
I'll tell you it takes a
little time to answer that,

00:47:31.649 --> 00:47:36.253 align:middle line:84%
but when they developed the
very first [inaudible] drug,

00:47:36.253 --> 00:47:37.988 align:middle line:90%
it was Merc [phonetic].

00:47:37.988 --> 00:47:41.292 align:middle line:84%
And it of us called
[inaudible] statin.

00:47:41.292 --> 00:47:45.796 align:middle line:84%
They have a director of
exploratory research by the name

00:47:45.796 --> 00:47:49.066 align:middle line:90%
of Doctor Karl Folkers.

00:47:49.066 --> 00:47:51.235 align:middle line:90%
And he told the company

00:47:51.235 --> 00:47:54.138 align:middle line:84%
that this drug we're
developing lowers cholesterol,

00:47:54.138 --> 00:47:55.272 align:middle line:90%
but it does something else.

00:47:55.272 --> 00:47:58.475 align:middle line:90%
It depletes Coenzyme Q10.

00:47:58.475 --> 00:48:00.878 align:middle line:90%
They filed two patents.

00:48:00.878 --> 00:48:03.514 align:middle line:90%
So nobody else could do it.

00:48:03.514 --> 00:48:06.750 align:middle line:84%
Other companies would have
added it to their drugs,

00:48:06.750 --> 00:48:10.054 align:middle line:90%
but Merc kept it quiet.

00:48:10.054 --> 00:48:13.857 align:middle line:84%
There's a patent request
by Doctor Julian Whitaker,

00:48:13.857 --> 00:48:17.294 align:middle line:84%
for several years now,
the petition to the FDA,

00:48:17.294 --> 00:48:20.230 align:middle line:90%
that they must warn all people

00:48:20.230 --> 00:48:21.932 align:middle line:84%
that if you're taking
any statin drugs,

00:48:21.932 --> 00:48:24.835 align:middle line:90%
you must take Coenzyme Q10.

00:48:24.835 --> 00:48:27.237 align:middle line:84%
And you can actually
put a person

